     <h2>Types of Investors in an IPO</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Retail Investors (RII):</strong>
      Individual investors applying for shares worth up to ₹2 lakh.
      Allotment is done via lottery when the issue is oversubscribed.
    </li>

    <li>
      <strong>HNI / NII (High Net-worth / Non-Institutional Investors):</strong>
      Investors applying for more than ₹2 lakh.
      Allotment is proportional, not lottery-based.
    </li>

    <li>
      <strong>QIB (Qualified Institutional Buyers):</strong>
      Large institutions like mutual funds, banks, and insurance companies.
      Their participation indicates confidence in the IPO.
    </li>

    <li>
      <strong>Anchor Investors:</strong>
      A special category of QIBs who invest a day before the IPO opens.
      Anchor investment boosts credibility and market confidence.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <p class="text-muted">
    Strong participation across categories generally reflects healthy demand for an IPO.
  </p>

